      <port>8000/tcp</port>
      <nvt oid="1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.104477">
        <type>nvt</type>
        <name>Python DoS Vulnerability (Oct 2022) - Linux</name>
        <family>Denial of Service</family>
        <cvss_base>7.5</cvss_base>
        <severities score="7.5">
          <severity type="cvss_base_v3">
            <origin>NVD</origin>
            <date>2022-11-09T21:17:00Z</date>
            <score>7.5</score>
            <value>CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H</value>
          </severity>
        </severities>
        <tags>cvss_base_vector=CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H|summary=Python is prone to a denial of service (DoS) vulnerability.|insight=An unnecessary quadratic algorithm exists in one path when
  processing some inputs to the IDNA (RFC 3490) decoder, such that a crafted, unreasonably long name
  being presented to the decoder could lead to a CPU denial of service. Hostnames are often supplied
  by remote servers that could be controlled by a malicious actor. In such a scenario, they could
  trigger excessive CPU consumption on the client attempting to make use of an attacker-supplied
  supposed hostname. For example, the attack payload could be placed in the Location header of an
  HTTP response with status code 302.|affected=Python prior to version 3.7.16, versions 3.8.x prior to 3.8.16,
  3.9.x prior to 3.9.16, 3.10.x prior to 3.10.9 and version 3.11.0.|impact=|solution=Update to version 3.7.16, 3.8.16, 3.9.16, 3.10.9, 3.11.1 or
  later.|vuldetect=Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.|solution_type=VendorFix</tags>
        <solution type="VendorFix">Update to version 3.7.16, 3.8.16, 3.9.16, 3.10.9, 3.11.1 or
  later.</solution>
